DTSTART:20260409T160000Z
DTEND:20260409T170000Z
LOCATION:LOWELL E. BAIER HALL/IU MAURER SCHOOL OF LAW - Room Number: 335
GEO:39.165074;-86.526424
SUMMARY:CACR Speaker Series talk | Ben Zhao-Professor of Computer Science
  at University of Chicago.┬Ā
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;Title: Societal impact and the ivory tower: an generat
 ive AI perspective  &#160\;Abstract: It is undeniable that computing rese
 arch has the power to rapidly reshape the world we live in\, and AI is li
 terally proving this point in real time. But even as we push to improve t
 hese models and architectures\, we are seeing today how economic motives 
 are shaping messaging and perception around AI's limitations and harms\, 
 posing ethical questions most of us are ill-equipped to answer. In this t
 alk\, I argue that we CS researchers must be more accountable for not jus
 t our research results\, but how they are deployed in applications. Recog
 nizing such impacts is arguably a very challenging task itself. Using my 
 own experience in recent AI security projects\, I describe the duality of
  AI's impact today\, both in real harms it has produced via misuse\, and 
 in protective benefits it can provide. I share some of the ethical questi
 ons we faced when considering the design and deployment of our tools Glaz
 e and Nightshade\, and our experiences through this process. Finally\, I 
 suggest some takeaways\, including possible perspectives on evaluating ne
 w research directions through an ethical downstream lens\, as well as som
 e concrete research questions that offer potential for positive technical
  and societal impact.  &#160\;  Ben Zhao is Neubauer Professor of Compute
 r Science at University of Chicago. He completed his Ph.D. at U.C. Berkel
 ey (2004)\, and B.S. from Yale (1997). He is a Fellow of the ACM\, TED/AI
  speaker\, and a recipient of the NSF CAREER award\, MIT Technology Revie
 w's TR-35 Award (Young Innovators Under 35)\, TIME100/AI (100 Influential
  people in AI)\, USENIX Internet Defense Prize\, Concept Art Association'
 s Community Impact Award\, ComputerWorld Magazine's Top 40 Technology Inn
 ovators award\, IEEE ITC Early Career Award\, and Faculty awards from Goo
 gle\, Amazon\, and Facebook. His work has been covered by many media outl
 ets including New York Times\, CNN\, NBC\, ABC\, BBC\, MIT Tech Review\, 
 Wall Street Journal\, Forbes\, and New Scientist. His current research fo
 cuses on mitigating the harms of misused AI. He has published over 190 ar
 ticles in areas of security and privacy\, machine learning\, networking\,
  and HCI. He served as TPC (co-)chair for the World Wide Web conference (
 WWW 2016) and ACM Internet Measurement Conference (IMC 2018)\, and on the
  Steering Committee of IEEE Conference on Secure and Trustworthy Machine 
 Learning (SaTML).
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><picture class="lw_image lw_image30087  l
 w_align_left"><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://events.iu.edu/liv
 e/image/scale/2x/gid/573/width/160/height/160/30087_Screenshot_2026-02-06
 _at_2.06.53PM.webp 2x\, https://events.iu.edu/live/image/scale/3x/gid/573
 /width/160/height/160/30087_Screenshot_2026-02-06_at_2.06.53PM.webp 3x" d
 ata-origin="responsive"/><source type="image/png" srcset="https://events.
 iu.edu/live/image/scale/2x/gid/573/width/160/height/160/30087_Screenshot_
 2026-02-06_at_2.06.53PM.rev.1771266939.png 2x\, https://events.iu.edu/liv
 e/image/scale/3x/gid/573/width/160/height/160/30087_Screenshot_2026-02-06
 _at_2.06.53PM.rev.1771266939.png 3x" data-origin="responsive"/><img width
 ="160" height="160" alt="" data-alt="" data-decoration="true" src="https:
 //events.iu.edu/live/image/gid/573/width/160/height/160/30087_Screenshot_
 2026-02-06_at_2.06.53PM.rev.1771266939.png" title="Screenshot 2026-02-06 
 at 2.06.53 PM" srcset="https://events.iu.edu/live/image/scale/2x/gid/573/
 width/160/height/160/30087_Screenshot_2026-02-06_at_2.06.53PM.rev.1771266
 939.png 2x\, https://events.iu.edu/live/image/scale/3x/gid/573/width/160/
 height/160/30087_Screenshot_2026-02-06_at_2.06.53PM.rev.1771266939.png 3x
 " data-max-w="712" data-max-h="712" loading="lazy" data-optimized="true"/
 ></picture></p><p>  &#160\;</p><p><strong>Title:</strong> Societal impact
  and the ivory tower: an generative AI perspective</p><p>  &#160\;</p><p>
 <strong>Abstract:</strong> It is undeniable that computing research has t
 he power to rapidly reshape the world we live in\, and AI is literally pr
 oving this point in real time. But even as we push to improve these model
 s and architectures\, we are seeing today how economic motives are shapin
 g messaging and perception around AI's limitations and harms\, posing eth
 ical questions most of us are ill-equipped to answer. In this talk\, I ar
 gue that we CS researchers must be more accountable for not just our rese
 arch results\, but how they are deployed in applications. Recognizing suc
 h impacts is arguably a very challenging task itself. Using my own experi
 ence in recent AI security projects\, I describe the duality of AI's impa
 ct today\, both in real harms it has produced via misuse\, and in protect
 ive benefits it can provide. I share some of the ethical questions we fac
 ed when considering the design and deployment of our tools Glaze and Nigh
 tshade\, and our experiences through this process. Finally\, I suggest so
 me takeaways\, including possible perspectives on evaluating new research
  directions through an ethical downstream lens\, as well as some concrete
  research questions that offer potential for positive technical and socie
 tal impact.</p><p>  &#160\;</p><p>  Ben Zhao is Neubauer Professor of Com
 puter Science at University of Chicago. He completed his Ph.D. at U.C. Be
 rkeley (2004)\, and B.S. from Yale (1997). He is a Fellow of the ACM\, TE
 D/AI speaker\, and a recipient of the NSF CAREER award\, MIT Technology R
 eview's TR-35 Award (Young Innovators Under 35)\, TIME100/AI (100 Influen
 tial people in AI)\, USENIX Internet Defense Prize\, Concept Art Associat
 ion's Community Impact Award\, ComputerWorld Magazine's Top 40 Technology
  Innovators award\, IEEE ITC Early Career Award\, and Faculty awards from
  Google\, Amazon\, and Facebook. His work has been covered by many media 
 outlets including New York Times\, CNN\, NBC\, ABC\, BBC\, MIT Tech Revie
 w\, Wall Street Journal\, Forbes\, and New Scientist. His current researc
 h focuses on mitigating the harms of misused AI. He has published over 19
 0 articles in areas of security and privacy\, machine learning\, networki
 ng\, and HCI. He served as TPC (co-)chair for the World Wide Web conferen
 ce (WWW 2016) and ACM Internet Measurement Conference (IMC 2018)\, and on
  the Steering Committee of IEEE Conference on Secure and Trustworthy Mach
 ine Learning (SaTML).</p>
